               <msContents class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85100084">
                  <summary change="#add-summary"> 1 copy of Makhzan al-asrār by Niẓāmī </summary>
                  <msItem xml:id="Uk_Or_11919-item1">
                     <author>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" type="standard"
                           key="ark:/81055/vdc_100166176939.0x000001 viaf_2474895">Niẓāmī</persName>
                        <persName xml:lang="fa"
                           key="ark:/81055/vdc_100166176939.0x000001 viaf_2474895">نظامی</persName>
                     </author>
                     <title xml:lang="fa-Latn-x-lc" key="work_3764">Makhzan al-asrār</title>
                     <title xml:lang="fa" key="work_3764">مخزن الاسرار</title>
                     <colophon xml:lang="fa">کتبه العبد الفقیر الحقیر...جعفر التبریزی...فی سنة ثمان
                        و ثلاثین و ثمانمائه الهجریة النبویة بدار السلطنة هراة</colophon>
                     <colophon>(f. 13r) Completed in Herat in 838 AH (1434/35) by <persName
                           role="scr" key="viaf_96545591">Jaʻfar al-Tabrīzī</persName>. </colophon>
                     <textLang mainLang="fa">Persian</textLang>
                     <note>Text lacks initial right hand page. </note>
                  </msItem>
               </msContents>
               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc form="codex">
                     <supportDesc material="chart">
                        <extent>13 ff <dimensions type="leaf" unit="cm">
                              <height>22</height>
                              <width>14.7</width>
                           </dimensions>
                        </extent>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout columns="4" ruledLines="25">
                           <p>25 lines per page in 4 columns except for f. 1r which has 3 columns,
                              the leftmost diagonal. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <handDesc>
                     <summary/>
                     <handNote>
                        <p>Nastaʻlīq; copied in black ink, with red, blue and gold headings. Copyist
                           is <persName role="scr" key="viaf_96545591">Jaʻfar
                           al-Tabrīzī</persName>.</p>
                     </handNote>
                  </handDesc>
                  <decoDesc>
                     <decoNote>(<locus>F. 1r</locus>). Blue and gold polychrome panels top and
                        bottom, set within illuminated surround, originally part of a double page
                        opening; f. 1v has illuminated headpiece; blue and gold text frames.
                     </decoNote>
                  </decoDesc>
                  <additions> <p>Folio 13v contains seals (see below) and 3 damaged inspection
                        notes, one dated 17 Ziʼl-Qaʻdah year 24 of an unspecified ruler; two
                        inscriptions recording the total number of folios as 21; and a reverse
                        impression from a facing page recording the previous owner (<hi
                           rend="italic">az bābat-i amvāl-i</hi>) as one Mīrzā ʻAlī Bayg. </p> 
                        <p>Typed note, presumably by Manuk, inserted after f. 13, claiming an
                        inspection dated regnal year 26 and two seals with the name of Aurangzeb. </p>
                     <p>Manuk number: M.33. </p>
                     <p>Endpaper: ‘Bequeathed by P.C. Manuk Esq. July 1949'; rear pastedown includes
                        his monogram 'PMC' . </p>
                  </additions>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding notBefore="1900" notAfter="1946">
                        <decoNote>Black 20th century European boards with gilt border around edge.
                        </decoNote>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
                  <sealDesc>
                     <seal subtype="circle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Circular seal: <hi rend="italic"><persName role="asn"
                                 key="viaf_138289888">Amānat Khān</persName> Shāh Jahānī sanah 5
                              sanah [10]42</hi> (1632/33). This seal survives as a mirror image only
                           on (<locus>f. 13v</locus>) presumably from a now missing facing page.
                        </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal subtype="circle" type="stamp">
                        <p>Circular seal: <hi rend="italic"><persName role="asn" key="person_f8368"
                                 >Sayyid 'Alī  [al-Ḥusaynī</persName> murīd-i Pād]shāh 'Ālam'gīr
                              10[75] </hi> (1665/66) (<locus>f. 13v</locus>). Identified on the
                           basis of better copies in other mss. </p>
                     </seal>
                     <seal>
                        <p>Circular seal: <hi rend="italic"><persName role="asn" key="person_f7021"
                                 >ʻAbd Allāh</persName> khānah'zād-i ʻĀlam'gīr Pādshāh sanah</hi>
                           [1093 (1682/83)] (<locus>f. 13v</locus>). Dated on the basis of other
                           examples. </p>
                     </seal>
                  </sealDesc>
               </physDesc>
               <history>
                  <origin>
                     <origDate calendar="Hijri-qamari" notBefore="1434" notAfter="1435">838 AH
                        (1434/35); </origDate>
                     <origPlace>Herat</origPlace>
                  </origin>
                  <provenance>Copied originally in Herat, it belonged to one Mīrzā ʻAlī Bayg. During
                     the reigns of Shah Jahan and Aurangzeb it was part of the Mughal Imperial
                     Library. </provenance>
                  <acquisition><p>Bequeathed to the British Museum by <persName
                           key="person_315725660" ref="https://viaf.org/en/viaf/315725660"
                           role="fmo">P.C. Manuk</persName> and <persName key="person_315725661"
                           ref="https://viaf.org/en/viaf/315725661" role="fmo">Miss G.M.
                           Coles</persName>, through the National Art Collections Fund,<date
                           calendar="#Gregorian" when="1949-07">July 1949</date>. Transferred to the
                        British Library in <date calendar="#Gregorian" when="1973"
                     >1973</date>.</p></acquisition>
               </history>
